<TEXT>
vice president dan quayle stopped in 
alaska on monday and reassured officials that cleanup work is not 
over on the oilsmeared beaches of prince william sound 
the job is not complete quayle said during a brief refueling 
stop en route to korea japan and the philippines you have our 
assurance that we will stay until the job is complete 
quayle was referring to the coast guards role as federal 
coordinator in valdez coast guard commandant paul yost has been 
monitoring exxons cleanup work since three weeks after the march 24 
wreck of the tanker exxon valdez 
the tanker spilled nearly 11 million gallons of oil into prince 
william sound after slamming into a reef resulting in the nations 
worst oil spill 
exxon declared its summer cleanup finished on friday the company 
said dwindling sunlight and deteriorating weather made further work 
this year unsafe 
quayles visit came as president bush visited the northwest in a 
swing through south dakota montana and washington bush defended 
his decision not to travel to alaska saying he had sent his 
environmental vice president 
during his visit quayle spent about a halfhour with alaskas 
oiled mayors the mayors of five coastal communities where 
crude continues to wash up on shore and where fishing fleets 
generally were tied up for the summer 
last may quayle inspected the oil spill cleanup on smith island 
quayle said monday it would not surprise him to learn that parts of 
the island among the first and hardest hit by the spill remain 
oily months after cleanup began 
the alaska mayors apparently won no new promises of action from 
the administration 
but kodiak mayor robert b brodie said quayle seemed to listen to 
the mayors concerns about the federal cleanup role next spring 
we told him the spills not over just because exxon has 
completed work and gone brodie said 
the vice president also met briefly with driftnet fishermen who 
are concerned about the bush administrations new agreement aimed at 
restricting driftnet fleets from taiwan korea and japan from 
fishing the north pacific ocean for squid 
us fishermen oppose the use of driftnets by foreign fleets 
because they contend the lightweight nets illegally harvest 
thousands of tons of salmon and steelhead 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

