<TEXT>
court proceedings were instituted 
against the leader of the southwest africa peoples organization by 
a group seeking information about hundreds of people the guerrilla 
movement allegedly detained 
swapo president sam nujoma who returned last week after 30 years 
in exile was served with court papers monday by a deputy sheriff 
following the legal move by the parents committee of namibia 
the committee alleged that swapo has failed to account for about 
1400 people who were put to work at guerrilla bases in angola 
during the movements 23year bush war against south african rule in 
neighboring namibia 
south africa has agreed to grant the territory independence and 
swapo is favored to win unsupervised elections in november for an 
assembly that will draft a constitution 
swapo contends that it complied with the un independence plan 
by releasing all prisoners in its custody 
but the parents committee in documents filed with the 
territorial supreme court claimed 1400 people either remain in 
swapo prison camps or have disappeared the committee called on 
swapo to account for the whereabouts of the missing people 
a un delegation is due back in namibia soon after a trip to 
angola and zambia to determine whether any prisoners are at swapo 
camps 
according to freed detainees hundreds of swapo members were 
accused of being south african spies and many were tortured until 
they signed confessions swapo leaders have confirmed incidents of 
torture and have countered that the south africanled security 
forces also were guilty of brutality 
</TEXT>
