<TEXT>
the vatican said today that a roman catholic 
convent of carmelite nuns near the auschwitz death camp in poland 
should be moved to another site as jewish groups have sought 
breaking its silence on an issue that has severely strained 
jewishcatholic relations the vatican said it would help to pay for 
a prayer center in which the nuns would live 
jewish leaders in the united states applauded the statement and 
said it would improve jewishcatholic relations 
a february 1987 accord between jewish and roman catholic 
representatives stipulated that the nuns would be moved to the 
prayer center from a convent just outside auschwitz jews have 
objected to their presence at a site where 25 million jews were 
murdered by the nazis during world war ii 
however the polish primate cardinal josef glemp has called for 
renegotiating the agreement and said the polish church did not have 
the money to build a new home for the nuns 
the agreement signed in geneva called for the nuns to have been 
moved by feb 22 but the deadline passed and the nuns remained 
glemp on a 24hour visit to bristol england to consecrate a 
polish catholic church indicated he had not read the vatican 
statement 
based on what reporters had told him about the statement he 
said this would seem to be a forceful resolution of the problem 
and i dont think that would be a very positive way of resolving 
it 
but glemp also said there is a possibility that the nuns could 
move elsewhere 
but if they were to be moved this should be done with charity 
because even if we were to transfer these nuns to a different 
location that would also be crossing out their rights he said 
the archbishop of krakow cardinal franciszek macharski said 
last month that the church was abrogating the agreement since it 
could not be fulfilled in an atmosphere of aggressive demands 
the vaticans commission for religious relations with judaism 
