<TEXT>
vermonts supreme court ruled today that 
one of its retired justices was guilty of judicial misconduct for 
helping a female friend who was a lowercourt judge 
the ruling said retired justice william hill committed seven 
ethics violations primarily for sitting on cases involving former 
assistant judge jane wheel and for intimidating the state attorney 
general by personally delivering a letter urging that a criminal 
probe of wheel be speeded up 
hill 72 was one of three supreme court justices charged with 
misconduct in 1987 by the judicial conduct board an arm of the 
court the board alleged the three improperly used their clout to 
help wheel then an assistant judge in chittenden county in a 
variety of matters 
the charges threw the fivemember court into turmoil gov 
madeleine kunin asked the three to step aside while the accusations 
were examined they refused but disqualified themselves from all 
cases involving anyone involved in the complaints which affected 
hundreds of cases 
the charges against justice ernest gibson iii were dropped for 
lack of a case justice thomas hayes died before the allegations 
against him were resolved 
a court employee testified that wheel had been seen with her arms 
around hill but hill and wheel testified they were not close and 
did not have an affair hill described their relationship as 
collegial 
the judicial conduct board found hill guilty of 11 counts of 
misconduct but it was up to the states high court to decide hills 
fate today the high court dismissed four counts but upheld the 
others 
a judge can never avoid the prestige and authority of the 
office he or she holds said the court that prestige and 
authority however may not be used to enhance personal 
relationships or for selfish reasons or to bestow favors 
the court said it would hear arguments next week on what 
sanctions to impose against hill because hill is retired the 
sanctions range from a reprimand to suspension from service as a 
substitute justice on high court cases 
hills pension will not be affected 
hills lawyer michael marks said he and hill felt the decision 
was a mixed bag 
the case was heard by a specially assigned court since most of 
the members who sat on the court with hill disqualified themselves 
wheel was convicted in a separate criminal case involving 
allegations she billed the state for days she did not work 
