<DOCNO> AP890919-0157 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the library of congress announced tuesday the 
first 25 american movie classics to be placed on the new national 
film registry as culturally historically or esthetically 
significant treasures in the art form of filmmaking 
the list was heavy with popular academy awardwinning titles 
from the best years of our lives to the wizard of oz it 
included one documentary nanook of the north and one 
contemporary hit 1977s star wars 
librarian of congress james h billington said the selections 
dont constitute a list of the best american movies but most are 
easily recognizable among moviegoers alltime favorites 
the 25 listed alphabetically 
the best years of our lives 1946 casablanca 1942 
citizen kane 1941 the crowd 1928 dr strangelove or 
how i learned to stop worrying and love the bomb 1964 the 
general 1927 gone with the wind 1939 the grapes of 
wrath 1940 high noon 1952 intolerance 1916 the 
learning tree 1969 and the maltese falcon 1941 
also mr smith goes to washington 1939 modern times 
1936 nanook of the north 1922 on the waterfront 1954 
the searchers 1956 singin in the rain 1952 snow white 
and the seven dwarfs 1937 some like it hot 1959 star 
wars 1977 sunrise 1927 sunset boulevard 1950 
vertigo 1958 and the wizard of oz 1939 
billington sought to defuse an almost certain controversy among 
film critics and scholars over the selections 
make no mistake this list of 25 films is not a list of the 
best 25 american films he said film critics and scholars could 
not agree on such a list and the library of congress would not 
embark on any such futile exercise this is not academy awards 
night 
rather he said the list should suggest to the american public 
the breadth of great american filmmaking under guidelines set by 
congress 
no films less than 10 years old were eligible and there was only 
one issued in the past 20 
the registry was created by congress last year as part of the 
national film preservation act which called for naming 25 
outstanding movies to the registry at the library of congress 
annually for three years 
the legislation was prompted partly by the recent boom in 
coloring of black and white films a practice loudly protested by 
moviemakers 
the law does not prevent coloring but any film listed in the 
national film registry must carry a warning label if it has been 
colorized or materially altered in versions produced for video 
cassettes television broadcast or other showings 
three directors whose films were chosen elia kazan billy wilder 
and stanley donen said congress should halt colorization 
they should take the next step to protect those films from all 
kinds of distortion speeding up colorization and all the other 
things that have been done to them and leave them the way we made 
them kazan said that is what they can do to really show how 
they honor our films 
seven of the winning films are owned by broadcasting magnate ted 
turner who is a champion of film colorization 
dave kehr chairman of the national society of film critics and a 
member of the national film preservation board said that the movies 
chosen made up a very safe conservative list but that he wished 
they had been a little more reflective of breadandbutter 
hollywood 
each film added to the governments version of a movie hall of 
fame will bear a seal designating it as an enduring part of our 
national cultural heritage 
the library of congress will obtain a highquality print of the 
original version of the movie for its collection of more than 75000 
film and television titles dating to the 19th century 
billington said half of all movies made before 1950 and 80 
percent of those made before 1930 have been lost forever because of 
the deterioration of early nitrate film into powder and because of 
sloppy cuts and editing of films for videotapes and tv broadcasts 
the cold hard fact is that for all their popularity in america 
today films are an endangered species for the america of 
tomorrow billington said 
the list is the result of a lengthy process involving nominations 
of nearly 1000 movie titles by mail from the general public the 
list was narrowed substantially by the 13 members of the new 
national film preservation board which met in los angeles in july 
billington made the final selection of the 25 top films and 
indicated tuesday that he personally made at least one addition to 
the list which he refused to identify he said there was no 
overwhelming alltime favorite nominated by the public or chosen by 
the panel of experts 
the board included representatives of the academy of motion 
picture arts and sciences the american film institute the 
directors guild of america the motion picture association of 
america the national association of broadcasters the national 
society of film critics the screen actors guild of america the 
writers guild of america movie and tv producers and film scholars 
billington said his goals in selecting the outstanding films were 
to help promote movies as an indigenous american art form and 
generate public interest in preserving films 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

