<TEXT>
the battleship new jersey fired its 16inch 
guns on tuesday the second battleship to do so since 47 sailors 
were killed in an april explosion aboard the uss iowa 
navy spokesman cmdr mark baker said the new jersey fired its 
weapons successfully off the california coast 
the ships nine guns in three turrets each fired three times 
resulting in 27 successful rounds 
the firing was approved by the pacific fleet commander adm 
david jeremiah baker said 
he said the firing of the guns was approved after the ship had 
completed an extensive review of its ordnance certification and 
training procedures as called for following the navy investigation 
into the april 19 explosion in the iowas no 2 turret 
the investigation was unable to pinpoint a cause but did cite 
gunners mate clayton hartwig captain of the middle gun as the 
most likely person to have caused the disaster 
the iowa first testfired the 16inch guns in its no 1 and no 3 
turrets on aug 4 while deployed in the mediterranean 
all iowaclas ships were prohibited from firing their guns 
immediately after the explosion but that decision was modified in 
june to allow for livefire training to prepare for 
contingency operations as directed by fleet commanders the navy 
said 
the navy has four battleship of the iowa class each of the guns 
can fire projectiles weighing up to 2700 pounds at a maximum range 
of 23 miles 
