<TEXT>
many aids patients die as a direct result of 
simply wasting away because their bodies are unable to retain enough 
food for adequate nourishment according to a study released tuesday 
by a columbia university researcher 
improving nutritional status provides a reasonable 
expectation for prolonging life and maintaining the quality of 
life for aids patients reports dr donald p kotler an associate 
professor at the columbias college of physicians and surgeons and 
the st lukesroosevelt hospital in new york 
in a study published in the american journal of clinical 
nutrition kotler estimated that 70 percent to 80 percent of aids 
patients die as a result of wasting away 
in studying the process kotler uses a measurement called body 
cell mass the weight of muscle and organs excluding fat bone and 
water outside the cells 
in a study 32 aids patients patients died when the bodycell 
mass dropped to an average of 54 percent of the ideal the study 
started 100 days before death when the average bodycell mass was 71 
percent of the ideal 
bodycell mass gives a more accurate picture of the state of 
malnutrition because patients can lose bodycell mass while not 
losing weight dramatically kotler said 
in a comments at a meeting tuesday of the federation of american 
societies of experimental biology kotler said the study did not 
determine the precise mechanism that causes death due to 
malnutrition among aids patients 
we do not know whether death is due to a general cellular 
starvation so that a critical number of cells stop functioning or 
some critical organ such as the brain liver kidneys or heart 
stops functioning he said 
dr c wayne callaway of george washington university told the 
meeting that kotlers study suggests that a control of malnutrition 
among aids patients might prolong life 
while we will have to wait on studies to prove that adequate 
nutrition can prolong life in aids patients from a doctors point 
of view i consider it only responsible to treat patients with the 
information that we have said callaway 
callaway said vomiting and diarrhea are the most common causes of 
malnutrition among aids patients and these symptoms often can be 
treated with drugs or food selection that will improve nutrition 
while nutrition does not solve the primary problem the aids 
viral infection it can improve the quality of patients lives he 
said many problems that cause malnutirition in aids patients are 
treatable by fairly simple interventions 
in another report at the meeting scientists from johns hopkins 
university in baltimore reported that they cleared all detectable 
signs of aids from a patient through a combination of radiation and 
chemotherapy to kill the patients bone marrow cells azt to prevent 
the aids virus from invading new cells and a bone marrow transplant 
the patient a 41yearold man died 46 days after the treatment 
from a type of cancer but no trace of aids genetic material could 
be detected in tissue samples from the patient 
even though the patient died we believe we demonstrated that 
he was cleared of all signs of the aids virus said dr rein 
saral a johns hopkins associate professor 
he cautioned the results should not be interpreted as a cure 
for aids because the virus could still have been present in some 
cells of the patients body 
</TEXT>
