<TEXT>
last weeks sharp selloff in the junk bond 
market could be a blessing in disguise for the economy by making it 
more difficult for companies to take on much more of the highcost 
debt some analysts say 
by scaring off investors the plunge in junk bonds could make it 
nearly impossible for companies to sell new junk issues unless there 
is a strong likelihood they are able to make payments on it over the 
long run said john lonski senior economist for moodys investors 
service 
you cant continue to leverage forever there has to be some 
end to whats taking place and sooner is better than later 
lonski said monday 
issuers of junk bonds are highinterestrate debt securities 
often used by companies with poor credit ratings must pay high 
interest rates to attract investors in recent years the securities 
have been widely used for such ventures as mergers and acquisitions 
but if the economy sours issuers could be forced to default 
adding to the economys troubles 
quoted bids for junk bonds stabilized monday after last weeks 
selloff although analysts said trading in the most speculative 
issues nearly ground to a halt 
people feel its too late to sell and too early to buy said 
marshall b front an economist at the chicago investment firm of 
stein roe amp farnham 
a cash crunch at campeau corp the canadian retailing giant 
triggered last weeks price plunge carrying down even relatively 
secure issues olympia amp york developments ltd conditionally agreed 
friday to loan campeau 250 million in a deal that was expected to 
give the toronto developer greater influence over campeaus 
management and a greater ownership stake 
after being carried downward by campeaus problems the 
highergrade junk bonds such as stone container corp kroger co 
owenscorning fiberglas corp and harcourt brace jovanovich inc 
were quoted as much as point higher monday a point equals 10 on 
a bond with a face value of 1000 
meanwhile the bid on one issue of campeaus allied stores corp 
unit was quoted down slightly to 26 cents on the dollar from 27 but 
with bond owners not willing to offer the issue at less than 35 
cents there was virtually no trading market participants said 
the bid for campeaus federated department stores inc bonds rose 
10 to 55 but was still well below the asking price of 65 
companies that were planning to issue junk bonds in coming weeks 
might postpone or restructure their offerings because of the 
selloff which pushed up yields and made financing more expensive 
lonski said 
if wary investors demand higher and higher interest on junk 
bonds companies may be less able to rely on the lowgrade 
securities for financing they then may either pull back from 
speculative riskier ventures or finance them in a less risky way 
such as by issuing stock 
the economy is approaching the seventh birthday of the longest 
us peacetime expansion in history but some economists say it may 
not last much longer 
